Here's the xUnit equivalent:

```csharp
// Per-test setup/teardown → constructor/IDisposable
// One-time setup/teardown → IClassFixture<T>

public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()  // replaces [OneTimeSetUp]
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()  // replaces [OneTimeTearDown]
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)  // replaces [SetUp]
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()  // replaces [TearDown]
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key mappings:
- **`[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`** → constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose()` (xUnit creates a new instance per test)
- **`[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`** → `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture class
- **`[Test]`** → `[Fact]`
- **`Assert.That(..., Is.EqualTo(...))` → `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)`** (note: expected comes first)

If you need async teardown, implement `IAsyncDisposable` instead.
